SIMPLE: pedagogue
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pedagogue
<hw>Ped"a*gogue</hw> <pr>(p⟦ecr⟧d"⟦asl⟧*g⟦ocr⟧g)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[F. <ets>p⟦eacute⟧dagogue</ets>, L. <ets>paedagogus</ets>, Gr.
<grk>paidagwgo`s</grk>; <grk>pai^s</grk>, <grk>paido`s</grk>, a boy +
<grk>'a`gein</grk> to lead, guide; cf. <grk>'agwgo`s</grk> leading. See
<er>Page</er> a servant, <er>Agent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Gr.
Antiq.)</fld> <def>A slave who led his master's children to school, and
had the charge of them generally.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A teacher of children; one whose occupation is to
teach the young; a schoolmaster.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who by teaching has become formal, positive, or
pedantic in his ways; one who has the manner of a schoolmaster; a
pedant.</def> <rj><au>Goldsmith.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pedagogue</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pedagogue
<hw>Ped"a*gogue</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. L.
<ets>paedagogare</ets> to instruct.]</ety> <def>To play the pedagogue
toward.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Prior.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pedagogy</ent>⟦br⟧
